--- [DEBUG] NARRATION LLM OUTPUT ---
The first generation of computers spans from the 1940s to the late 1950s, a period marked by rapid innovation following World War II. This era laid the foundation for modern computing by introducing electronic machines that could perform complex calculations much faster than humans.

At the heart of these early machines were vacuum tubes, which acted like tiny electronic switches to control the flow of electricity. Although bulky and prone to overheating, vacuum tubes were revolutionary, replacing slower mechanical parts and enabling the first truly electronic computers.

These computers were primarily electromechanical, combining electrical components with mechanical parts. They were often custom-built for specific tasks like code-breaking or scientific calculations, rather than the versatile, general-purpose computers we use today.

Size and power consumption were significant challenges. These machines filled entire rooms, requiring extensive cooling systems to prevent overheating. Their enormous size and high energy use highlight how far technology has advanced since then.

Programming these first-generation computers was a manual, labor-intensive process involving machine language or early assembly languages. Operators had to input instructions using punch cards or switches, making programming a specialized and time-consuming skill.
