--- [DEBUG] NARRATION LLM OUTPUT ---
When electrical signals enter the vacuum tube circuit, they are often very weak or unstable. Think of this as a faint whisper that needs to be heard clearly. The vacuum tube receives these signals to prepare them for further processing within the computer.

The vacuum tube uses a process called thermionic emission, where heat causes electrons to flow inside the tube. This flow amplifies the weak electrical signals, much like turning up the volume on a radio so the message becomes strong and clear enough to use.

In addition to amplification, vacuum tubes function as switches. They control the flow of electrical current, turning it on or off to represent the binary digits 1 and 0. This switching capability is essential for computers to perform logical operations and store data.

Once the signals are amplified and properly switched, they are sent to other parts of the computer. These processed signals carry the instructions and data needed for the machine to perform calculations and execute programs efficiently.
