--- [DEBUG] NARRATION LLM OUTPUT ---
Vacuum tubes were the heart of early computers, acting like tiny switches that controlled electrical signals. They operated much faster than mechanical parts, enabling quicker calculations, but they consumed a lot of power and generated heat, which often caused reliability issues.

Electromechanical parts, like relays and switches, physically moved to process information. While slower and bulkier than vacuum tubes, they were more durable and easier to repair. Their mechanical nature limited speed, but they laid important groundwork for automated computing before electronics took over.
