--- [DEBUG] NARRATION LLM OUTPUT ---
Konrad Zuse’s Z3 was a groundbreaking achievement because it was the first programmable electromechanical computer. Unlike earlier calculating machines, it could be programmed to perform different tasks, laying the foundation for modern computing flexibility.

The Colossus machine played a crucial role during World War II by using vacuum tubes to rapidly break encrypted German messages. This not only demonstrated the power of electronic computing but also had a direct impact on the outcome of the war.

ENIAC marked a major leap as the first general-purpose electronic digital computer. Using thousands of vacuum tubes, it could perform a variety of calculations much faster than any human or mechanical device, opening the door to electronic data processing.

The invention of the transistor at Bell Labs was revolutionary because it replaced bulky, fragile vacuum tubes. Transistors were smaller, more reliable, and energy-efficient, which eventually led to the miniaturization and increased power of computers.

UNIVAC I was the first commercial computer, showing that computing technology could be used beyond research and military purposes. Delivered to the US Census Bureau, it helped automate data processing on a large scale for government and business.

IBM’s 1401 became a popular business computer by combining vacuum tube technology with magnetic storage. It made computing accessible to many companies, helping to automate tasks like payroll and inventory, which transformed office work in the 1950s.
